                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 17

                                ---------------------------------------------
                                Chapter 5:  OVERVIEW OF USING THE MAIL SYSTEM
                                ---------------------------------------------


       Section 5.1  Downloading and Reading Mail Packets

       Before the  specific details  of installing  and using the mail reader
       are discussed,  let's examine  the way the mail reader should be used.
       This information  applies to  all offline  mail readers,  and  is  not
       specifically geared  toward The  Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader.  Since
       all offline  mail systems  operate in the same way, you may already be
       familiar with  the procedures used to retrieve mail packets, read mail
       packets, create  replies and  new messages, and uploading your replies
       and new messages to the host system for processing.

       Here is an outline of the steps you need to perform to retrieve a mail
       packet from a host mail system for reading with the mail reader:

            1)   Use your  communications program  to log  into your favorite
                 BBS which  provides offline  mail capabilities.  If a system
                 supports the  use of an offline mail system, it will usually
                 be referred to as an "Offline Mail Door".

            2)   Locate the  offline mail  packer used on the BBS.  This will
                 usually be  an option on the Main Menu, Message System Menu,
                 or Doors  Menu of  the BBS.   If  you are not sure where the
                 mail door  is located, or you do not know if the BBS you are
                 calling supports  the use  of an  offline mail  system,  you
                 should ask  the system  operator (SysOp)  of that system for
                 information.

            3)   Use the  mail system  while you  are connected to the BBS to
                 pack your selected messages.  Since all mail systems differ,
                 it is  impossible to  give you  specific instructions  about
                 this step.  You should consult with the SysOp of that BBS if
                 you are  having problems.   If the BBS you are dialing has a
                 Blue  Wave  Offline  Mail  Door  (written  by  Cutting  Edge
                 Computing), you  will find  specific instructions  for using
                 our mail  doors in  a file  called BWDOOR.DOC,  which should
                 have been  unpacked to  your reader directory.  If this file
                 is  not  there,  use  the  installation  program  to  unpack
                 documentation files.

            4)   Using  your  communications  program,  "download"  the  mail
                 packet that  is generated  by the  mail door.   All  of  the
                 messages that  were packed  by the  mail door should come to
                 you  in   one  file.    With  many  communication  programs,
                 initiating a  download is  often done by pressing the <PgDn>
                 key, or  pressing <Alt-D>.   This is not universal, however.
                 You should consult the documentation for your communications
                 program for  full details  on downloading  files, as  a full
                 discussion of  this  topic  is  beyond  the  scope  of  this
                 documentation.


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 18

            5)   Log off of the host mail system and exit your communications
                 program.

            6)   Load Blue  Wave and  select "Open Mail Packet" from the Main
                 Menu.   Find the mail packet you just downloaded in the list
                 of mail  packets that  is presented,  highlight  the  packet
                 using the  cursor keys  on your keyboard, and press <Enter>.
                 The mail  reader will then open up the mail packet and begin
                 the offline mail reading process.

                 **   If the packet that you just downloaded does not show up
                      in the  Packet Manager  Window, you  need to  go to the
                      "Setup/Configure Mail  Reader" item  on the  Main Menu,
                      move to  the "Directories"  pull-down menu,  and change
                      the  "Download   Directory"  so  that  it  matches  the
                      download  directory  in  your  communications  program.
                      Press <F1>  while editing the "Download Directory" item
                      for full details.

       At this  point you  have completed  the procedures  needed to download
       mail packets  and read them with the mail reader.  Remember, if at any
       time you need help when using the mail reader, press the <F1> key.



       Section 5.2  Creating and Uploading Reply Packets

       After you  have successfully  downloaded and read a mail packet, it is
       possible that  you  have  generated  replies,  new  messages,  offline
       configurations, or  file requests.  If you have done any of these, the
       mail reader will generate what is called a "reply packet".  This reply
       packet will be stored in the directory that you have configured in the
       mail reader  as  the  "Upload  Directory".    The  "Upload  Directory"
       configuration item is on the "Setup/Configure Mail Reader" menu, under
       the "Directories" pull-down menu.

       Your "Upload  Directory" should  be configured  to be  the same as the
       upload directory in your communications program.  If you configure the
       mail reader  in this  way, any  reply packets  generated by  the  mail
       reader  will  immediately  be  available  while  you  are  using  your
       communications program.

       Here is  an outline  of the  steps you  need to  perform to  send  (or
       upload) a mail packet from the mail reader's "Upload Directory" to the
       host mail system for processing.

            1)   Use your communications program to log into same system that
                 you downloaded  the original  mail packet  from.  You cannot
                 send a  reply packet  to a  BBS which  did  not  create  the
                 original mail packet.

            2)   Use the  same "Mail  Door" or  mail packer  option that  you
                 downloaded the  mail packet from.  Please note that some BBS
                 systems  have   several  different  mail  packers  available
                 online.  It is important that you choose the correct one!

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 19


            3)   Use the  "Upload" command  while in the mail system to begin
                 the process  of sending  your reply  packet to the host BBS.
                 Since all  mail systems differ, it is impossible to give you
                 specific instructions  about this  step.  You should consult
                 with the  SysOp of  that BBS if you are having problems.  If
                 the BBS  you are  dialing has  a Blue Wave Offline Mail Door
                 (written by  Cutting Edge Computing), you will find specific
                 instructions for  using our  mail doors  in  a  file  called
                 BWDOOR.DOC, which  should have  been unpacked to your reader
                 directory.   If this file is not there, use the installation
                 program to unpack the documentation files.

            4)   Using your communications program, "upload" the reply packet
                 that was  generated by the mail reader.  All of the messages
                 that you  wrote should  have been  packed into one file with
                 the same 'root name' as the mail packet you downloaded.  For
                 example, if you download a mail packet through the Blue Wave
                 Support BBS,  it will be called WILDBLUE.xxx, where 'xxx' is
                 the  packet  extension  used  by  the  mail  door  for  that
                 particular download  session.  In this case, the mail reader
                 will have  generated a  file in  its "Upload Directory" with
                 the name  of "WILDBLUE.NEW".  If the mail door you are using
                 is a  QWK-style mail  packer (described  earlier), the  file
                 extension will be ".REP" instead of ".NEW".

                 Initiating an  upload through your communications program is
                 often done  by pressing the <PgUp> key, or pressing <Alt-U>.
                 This is  not universal,  however.   You should  consult  the
                 documentation  for  your  communications  program  for  full
                 details on  uploading files,  as a  full discussion  of this
                 topic is beyond the scope of this documentation.

                 **   If you  use  the  Zmodem  file  transfer  protocol  for
                      downloads,  you   may  find  that  your  communications
                      program automatically  starts  the  download  for  you.
                      This cannot  be done with Zmodem uploads, however.  You
                      MUST  initiate   the   file   transfer   through   your
                      communications  program  by  pressing  the  appropriate
                      key(s) (usually <PgUp> or <Alt-U>).

            5)   Log off of the host mail system and exit your communications
                 program.

       At this  point, you have completed the steps necessary to send a reply
       packet back  to the  host mail  system for  processing.  After doing a
       complete mail  download and  mail upload  cycle a  few times,  it will
       become second nature to you.  Do not get discouraged if you make a few
       mistakes in  the process;  everyone has gone through the same learning
       curve.






                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 20

                                      ---------------------------------------
                                      Chapter 6:  CONFIGURING THE MAIL READER
                                      ---------------------------------------

       Section 6.1  MS-DOS CONFIG.SYS Settings

       If you are using either Blue Wave/DOS or Blue Wave/386 under the MS-
       DOS (or compatible) operating system -- either alone or with Microsoft
       Windows -- you should make sure that the following items are set
       properly in your CONFIG.SYS file.

       CONFIG.SYS is  a system  startup configuration  file  that  is  always
       located  in  the  root  directory  of  the  DOS  boot  drive  (usually
       C:\CONFIG.SYS).   If you  do not  have a  CONFIG.SYS file,  it will be
       necessary to create one.

       Load CONFIG.SYS  into a  text editor  and make  sure there  is a  line
       somewhere which reads:

            FILES=25

       This line  tells DOS  at boot time to allocate 25 file handles for use
       by programs  that you  will be running on your system.  If you already
       have a "FILES=" line in your CONFIG.SYS, and the number after it is 25
       or higher,  there will  be no  problems.   A value higher than 25 will
       work just  fine, but  a lower  value can  cause problems.  If the mail
       reader attempts  to open  a file for reading or writing, and there are
       not enough DOS file handles available, the open will fail.

       The last  item to  check in  your CONFIG.SYS  file is  the  number  of
       buffers that  you  are  allowing  DOS  to  allocate  for  faster  disk
       accesses.   In your  CONFIG.SYS file,  you should  have  a  line  that
       contains the following:

            BUFFERS=30

       This tells  DOS to  allocate enough  system memory  to  hold  30  disk
       buffers.  This in turn allows DOS to perform disk intensive activities
       much more  quickly than  normal.   If the  number of  buffers in  your
       CONFIG.SYS file is already set higher than 30, that is perfectly fine.
       If you are running a disk caching program, you can ignore this advice,
       and follow  the instructions  that were given in the documentation for
       your disk  caching program.   Most disk caching programs will instruct
       you to use a very low value for the "BUFFERS=" statement in CONFIG.SYS
       because the  cache program can use the memory in a much more efficient
       manner than DOS does.


       Section 6.2  Creating a Blue Wave Icon Under Windows

       Users of  Microsoft Windows  v3.1x may  wish to  add an  icon to their
       Windows desktop  that will,  when selected,  load and execute the Blue
       Wave reader.   To  do so, follow the steps outlined below.  (Note that
       unless otherwise indicated, to "select" something is to move the mouse
       cursor over it and click on it.)

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 21


       For OS/2  users, we  do NOT  recommend installing the DOS reader under
       Win-OS/2.   Instead, we  recommend that  you install the reader to the
       OS/2 desktop,  as described  in the next section, due to the fact that
       Win-OS/2 does  not execute  DOS programs  in the same manner as "true"
       Windows.

       1.   Start Windows.

       2.   If you  are adding  the Blue  Wave icon  to an  existing  program
            group, skip to step 3.  Otherwise, perform the following steps to
            create a new program group.

            a.   Select File on the Program Manager menu bar, then select the
                 New option.

            b.   At the New Program Object dialog, select "Program Group" and
                 select OK.

            c.   At the  Program Group Properties dialog, enter the following
                 information in these fields:

                      Description:   Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader
                      Group File:    BLUEWAVE.GRP

                 and select OK.  The new group will now appear inside Program
                 Manager.

       3.   Make sure  the program  group in which you want to place the Blue
            Wave icon is active.  Do this by clicking on the title bar of the
            group dialog  box, or  if it  is minimized,  double-click on  its
            minimized icon to bring it up.

       4.   Select File  on the Program Manager menu bar, then select the New
            option.

       5.   At the  New Program  Object dialog,  select  "Program  Item"  and
            select OK.

       6.   At the  Program  Item  Properties  dialog,  enter  the  following
            information in these fields:

                 Description:        Blue Wave
                 Command Line:       BWAVE.EXE
                 Working Directory:  C:\BWAVE       (or path you specified
                                                    during installation)

            Do NOT select OK; instead, select Change Icon.  You will probably
            see an error dialog box which states that no icons are available.
            No sweat;  this is  normal.   Select OK,  and at  the Change Icon
            dialog box, select Browse.

       8.   At the  Browse dialog  box, enter  E:\BWAVE\BWAVE.ICO in the File
            Name field  (use the  path you  specified  during  installation).
            Select OK, then select OK at the Change Icon dialog box.

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 22


       9.   At the  New Program Object dialog box, you should now see an icon
            in the  lower left corner that looks like... a blue wave!  Select
            OK.

       You should  now see  an icon  in your  selected program group with the
       name "Blue  Wave".   Double-click on  this icon, and the reader should
       start up just as if you executed it from the DOS command line.

       Note that  this procedure  can also  be used  for  the  Blue  Wave/386
       reader.  Simply substitute "BWAVE386.EXE" for "BWAVE.EXE", and for the
       icon title, "Blue Wave/386" for "Blue Wave".

       At the  time of  this writing, we have not tested the operation of the
       DOS reader  under Windows  NT v3.x  or Windows 95.  As such, we cannot
       guarantee their  operation under  those operating systems; however, we
       do not foresee any problems in this regard.


       Section 6.3  Creating a Blue Wave Icon Under OS/2

       If you  are using  IBM OS/2  v2.x or Warp v3.x, you may wish to add an
       icon to OS/2's Workplace Shell (WPS) desktop that will, when selected,
       load and  execute the Blue Wave reader.  The steps to install both the
       DOS and OS/2 readers onto the WPS desktop are given below.  (Note that
       unless otherwise indicated, to "select" something is to move the mouse
       cursor over it and click on it.)

       Note that instructions for installing the Blue Wave/386 reader are not
       given.   This is  primarily due  to the  fact that the 386 reader is a
       "CPU hog" (on top of the overhead generated by DOS sessions), and will
       bog down  the rest  of your  system if you routinely multitask several
       applications.  Also, the OS/2 reader offers the same advantages as the
       386 reader,  without being  a CPU  hog, so there's little advantage to
       running the 386 reader under OS/2.


       To install the DOS reader on the OS/2 desktop:

       1.   Open the  Templates folder.   Move  the cursor  over the  Program
            template and, while holding down the right mouse button, drag the
            template onto  the desktop.   Release the button, and the Program
            Settings notebook will appear.

       2.   Enter the following information into these fields:

                 Path and File Name:      C:\BWAVE\BWAVE.EXE
                 Working Directory:       C:\BWAVE

            Note that  you should  use the  directory  you  specified  during
            installation, if it is a directory other than C:\BWAVE.

       3.   Select the  Session notebook  tab.  Decide if you wish to run the
            reader full-screen  or in  a window,  and select  the appropriate
            option.

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 23


       4.   Select the General notebook tab.  In the Title field, enter "Blue
            Wave".

       5.   Close the object by double-clicking its icon in the upper left
            corner.

       You should  now see  an icon  (which looks  like a  blue wave!) on the
       desktop with the name "Blue Wave".  Double-click on this icon, and the
       reader should  start up  just as  if you  had executed  it from  a DOS
       session command line.


       To install the OS/2 reader on the OS/2 desktop:

       1.   Open a windowed or full-screen OS/2 session.

       2.   Change to  the directory  in which you installed the reader (i.e.
            "CD C:\BWAVE") and start the reader by typing "BWAVE2".

       3.   At the Main Menu, select the Setup/Configure Mail Reader option.

       4.   At the  setup menu,  move the cursor to the Global pull-down menu
            and select the Create WPS Desktop Icon option.

       5.   When asked  if you  want to  install to  the OS/2 desktop, select
            "Yes".

       6.   Decide if  you wish to run the reader full-screen or in a window.
            Select "Yes" to run full-screen, or "No" to run in a window.

       7.   A message will display confirming that the icon has been created.
            Exit the reader and return to the OS/2 desktop.

       You should  now see  an icon  (which looks  like a  blue wave!) on the
       desktop with  the name  "Blue Wave/2".  Double-click on this icon, and
       the reader should start up just as if you had executed it from an OS/2
       session command line.

       An alternate  method is  to use  the same  instructions for  the  OS/2
       reader as  was given for the DOS reader (above).  However, because the
       OS/2 reader  has a  built-in ability to install itself to the desktop,
       doing things the "long way" is not really necessary.



       Section 6.4  Configuring and Installing External Programs

       Configuring external  programs for use with The Blue Wave Offline Mail
       Reader is perhaps the single most important aspect of getting the mail
       reader to  work properly.   Close to 100% of the problems that you may
       encounter  while   using  the  mail  reader  are  due  to  incorrectly
       configured or  missing program  command lines.   This  section of  the
       documentation --  along with  the following sub-sections -- attempt to


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 24

       explain, in  great  detail,  the  proper  way  to  configure  external
       programs for use with the mail reader.

       It  is  important  to  remember  that  you  must  have  at  least  one
       compression program,  the corresponding  decompression program,  and a
       message editor  command line  defined in  order to  operate the reader
       successfully.   ZIP-formatted mail  packets are  so common  that it is
       almost  imperative   that  you   have  a   ZIP  compression   and  ZIP
       decompression program.   (Please  see Chapter  5 for  more information
       regarding required  external programs).   For  this reason, you should
       read the  following section  (6.5) very  carefully if  you are  having
       trouble getting a mail packet to open.



       Section 6.4.1  The PATH Environment Variable

       Throughout this  documentation, and  in many other program manuals you
       may read, you will see references to what is called "the system PATH",
       "the PATH environment variable", and "DOS (or OS/2) PATH".

       In order  to understand the configuration of external programs in this
       or any  other program,  it is  essential that you understand what this
       terminology is referring to.

       Each time you boot your computer, MS-DOS reads two configuration files
       from the  root directory  of your boot drive (usually C:\).  These two
       files are  called CONFIG.SYS  and AUTOEXEC.BAT.   The PATH environment
       variable is  configured in  the file AUTOEXEC.BAT under MS-DOS.  (Note
       that OS/2 uses the CONFIG.SYS file for setting the system PATH.)

       If you  load the  file AUTOEXEC.BAT  into a text file editor, you will
       probably see a line that reads:

            PATH c:\;c:\dos;c:\windows

       The names of the directories listed in this line may be different from
       above.   Each directory  name is  separated by a semi-colon (;).  If a
       program is  "located on  the system  PATH", it  simply means  that the
       file(s) needed  to run  this program  are in  one of  the  directories
       listed on  this line.   You  can add  new  directories  to  your  PATH
       statement by  simply editing  this line  to include  the new directory
       (make sure  that if  there are  any directories listed before or after
       the new  directory entry,  that you separate them with a semi-colon!).
       Under DOS,  the maximum  length of  this line  is 127  characters, and
       under OS/2 the maximum length of this line is 1024 characters.

       Please note that any changes you make to your CONFIG.SYS file and your
       AUTOEXEC.BAT file  will not  become effective  until you  REBOOT  your
       system.  They are only read by DOS and OS/2 once;  at system startup.

       When DOS,  OS/2, or  any program  running under  these  two  operating
       systems tries  to  run  a  program,  it  first  searches  the  current
       directory to see if the program is there.  If it is there, the program
       is run  from the  current directory.  If it is NOT there, DOS and OS/2

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 25

       begin searching  the directories listed in this line.  The directories
       are searched in the order they appear.  If, after searching the entire
       list of  directories contained  in this  line, the  program cannot  be
       found, DOS will issue this error message:

            Bad command or file name.

       The behavior  and use  of the  PATH environment  variable is described
       here because  DOS and  OS/2 will behave in the same manner as the mail
       reader when  it cannot  find a  program you  have told  it to  run  --
       although the  mail reader's  error messages  are a  bit more friendly.
       Any program  that you  try to  run through  the mail  reader  must  be
       located on the system PATH.

       The purpose  of  the  system  PATH  environment  variable  is  one  of
       convenience.   If a  program is  located in a directory located on the
       system path,  that program can be run from ANY directory you happen to
       be in.   For  example, when  you  install  Windows,  it  installs  the
       C:\WINDOWS directory  on the  system path.  No matter where you are on
       your computer,  typing "WIN"  will start  the Windows Program Manager.
       If you  were to  remove "C:\WINDOWS"  from the  system path and reboot
       your  machine,   you  would  be  required  to  be  in  the  C:\WINDOWS
       subdirectory before Windows could load.



       Section 6.5  Configuring External Archivers

       In order  to unpack  messages you  have downloaded  from a  host  mail
       system,  and   to  pack  reply  packets  that  you  have  created  for
       transmission back  to the  host system,  it is  necessary for the mail
       reader  to   spawn  (call,  execute,  run)  external  compression  and
       decompression  utilities.     When   this  documentation   refers   to
       "Archivers", it  is referring  to these  compression and decompression
       utilities.

       All archivers require that specific command line parameters be used in
       order to work properly.  Default archiver command lines are built into
       the  mail   reader  for  all  popular  compression  and  decompression
       programs, and should not be changed unless you are familiar with their
       operation.   While  editing  an  archiver  command  line  through  the
       "Setup/Configuration" menu of the mail reader, a window will appear on
       the screen  which says  "Press <F2> to load default command line".  If
       you have  the archiver  installed on your system, and this archiver is
       installed in  a directory  located on  your system  PATH (see  section
       6.4.1), the  mail reader will automatically assign the correct command
       line for  you when you press <F2>.  You should not need to change this
       command line.

       If, after  pressing <F2>,  the mail  reader displays  an error message
       informing you  that the  archiver cannot  be found,  you should  first
       determine if that particular archiver is available on your system.  If
       it is not, you will need to download it and install it before the mail
       reader will  be able  to open  any mail packets that have been created


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 26

       with this archiver.  Copy all the files needed to run this archiver to
       a directory on your system path (see section 6.4.1)

       Please note  that not  *all* archivers need to be installed to use the
       mail reader.   Most  people will  find that they never have to install
       anything but  ZIP, since most systems pack mail in this format.  There
       are a  few rare  instances where  you may  need an  ARJ, LHA,  ARC, or
       (increasingly hard to find) PAK archiver.

       The AUX  compression and decompression command lines will almost never
       be used.  If you want to learn more information about when and why the
       AUX compression  and decompression  command lines are used, please see
       the online  help for  the AUX  archivers by going to the SETUP menu of
       the reader,  moving to  the "Archivers"  pull-down menu,  highlighting
       either "AUX Compression" or "AUX Decompression", and pressing <F1>.



       Section 6.5.1  Notes About Archiver Command Lines

       PKZIP and  its companion program PKUNZIP are, by far, the most popular
       ZIP compression  and decompression utilities available for MS-DOS.  If
       you are  installing Blue Wave/DOS or Blue Wave/386, you should install
       PKZIP.EXE and PKUNZIP.EXE in a directory on your system which contains
       other important  system utilities.  At the time this documentation was
       written, version  2.04g  was  the  latest  available  version  of  the
       PKZIP/PKUNZIP utilities.

       If you  are using  OS/2, you  should find  and obtain  a copy  of  the
       InfoZip Project's  ZIP.EXE and  UNZIP.EXE for OS/2.  It is recommended
       that you  use ZIP  v2.01 or  later, and  UNZIP v5.12  or later, due to
       compatibility problems  with earlier  versions.    These  versions  of
       ZIP/UNZIP are  known to  work properly under OS/2.  If you cannot find
       these programs  locally, you  are welcome  to download  them from  our
       Support BBS.  The OS/2 version of the mail reader can load and run DOS
       archiver programs,  so you  can use  the MS-DOS  versions of PKZIP and
       PKUNZIP if  necessary.   However, using  the  DOS  versions  of  these
       compression programs is more time consuming, as OS/2 must launch a DOS
       session in order to pack and unpack messages.



       Section 6.6  Message Editor Command Line

       The Blue  Wave Offline  Mail Reader  requires the  use of  an external
       editor for  the purpose  of editing  replies and  new messages.   Blue
       Wave/DOS and  Blue Wave/386  come packaged  with a  very simple, small
       public domain editor called TED3 (Tiny Editor, version 3).  If you are
       not comfortable  using this  editor, or  you prefer to use a different
       editor for  any reason  at all, you should give the name of the editor
       you would like to use here.

       For example,  if you  have a  message editor  called EDITFILE.EXE, and
       this program  is located  on your  system PATH  (see  section  6.4.1),
       simply put "EDITFILE.EXE" in the message editor command line field.

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 27


       Blue Wave  automatically passes  a file  name to  be  edited  to  your
       message editor.   This  is done because your editor must know the name
       of the file to edit in order to work properly with the mail reader.

       If the  reader encounters  an '@F'  (without the quotes) in the editor
       command line,  it will  replace it  with the  file name of the message
       text to  be worked  on.   If '@F'  is not  found, the name of the file
       automatically gets passed as the last command line parameter.

       Suppose your  editor, EDITFILE.EXE,  requires a  "-w" be  typed on the
       command line  in order  to start  up in  word wrap  mode, and the "-w"
       command line  parameter must  come after the name of the file to edit.
       Your message editor command line would look like this:

            EDITFILE.EXE @F -w

       Blue Wave/OS2  does not come with the TED3 editor, since TED3 is a DOS
       program only.   Instead,  the mail  reader will  search for  the  OS/2
       System Editor, E.EXE.

       The message  editor command  line is  run each  time you  reply  to  a
       message, enter  a new message, or choose to edit a message through the
       Outbound Mail Manager.

       Please note  that you cannot use a Windows application as your message
       editor command  line.   Windows does  not allow a DOS program (such as
       Blue Wave/DOS or Blue Wave/386) to launch a Windows application.



       Section 6.7  Spell Checker Command Line

       The spell  checker command line is executed only on user demand;  that
       is, you  must actually  tell the mail reader to run this program.  You
       can run  the spell  checker command  line after  a  message  has  been
       entered or  replied to  (the mail  reader will present you with a menu
       which has  "Check Spelling"  as one of the choices).  In addition, you
       can run  the spelling  checker  from  the  Outbound  Mail  Manager  by
       pressing <C> or selecting "Spell Checker" in the pull-down menu.

       The same  rules apply for setting up the Spell Checker command line as
       for the  Message Editor  Command Line  (see section  6.6).   The spell
       checker command line also supports the use of the '@F' macro described
       for the  message editor  command line.   A  spelling checker  that  is
       commonly used  with The  Blue Wave  Offline Mail Reader is ShareSpell.
       If you  cannot locate  a copy  of ShareSpell  on a BBS near you, it is
       available for download through the Blue Wave Support BBS.



       Section 6.8  Terminal/Comm Command Line

       The reader  has a  quick and  convenient way  to access a user-defined
       terminal (communications)  program.   From anywhere  within  the  mail

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 28

       reader, you  can press  <Alt-T> to  execute the  Terminal/Comm Command
       Line.   In addition,  you can have the reader execute the command line
       immediately upon  startup by placing the "/TERM" switch on the command
       line.

       The same  rules for defining the terminal command line apply to all of
       the command lines defined within the mail reader.  Please see sections
       6.4.1 and 6.6 for more information.

       **   Please note  that this  command line  does not  actually have  to
            point to a communications program.  You can place type of program
            you like  here, and  the reader will load it when you press <Alt-
            T>.   You may decide that you would like to place an editor, file
            manager program,  or reference  materials in this command line to
            be called up at any time you are using the mail reader.

            In addition,  Blue Wave/DOS  and Blue  Wave/386 cannot  launch  a
            Windows application,  due to  a  limitation  in  Windows.    This
            command line must point to a valid DOS program when used with the
            /DOS and /386 mail readers.



       Section 6.9  Editor/Browser Command Line

       The reader  has a very simple built-in ASCII file viewer, or LIST-type
       program which  is available  by pressing  <Alt-L> from anywhere within
       the mail  reader.   This command line definition is supplied for those
       who would  like a more powerful file lister, such as Vernon D. Buerg's
       LIST.COM, to be accessible while using the mail reader.  If you do not
       place a  command line  here, the  reader will  use its  internal  file
       lister when <Alt-L> is used.

       This command  line uses  the same  rules as  all  previously-described
       command lines.   Please read the previous sections in this chapter for
       more information.





       Section 6.10  External Tagline Manager Command Line

       The Blue  Wave Offline  Mail Reader provides support for the use of an
       external tagline  manager/selection utility.  When you have configured
       the mail  reader to  use an external tagline manager, the command line
       you supply  here will be executed each time the selection of a tagline
       is required  (if the  mail reader's  tagline selection  type is set to
       'External' in the Preferences->Tagline Behavior Preferences section of
       the Setup menu).

       The mail reader only supports tagline managers that are "John Hancock"
       compatible.  The John Hancock tagline selection/beautification utility
       is a Shareware program written by Dan Moore.  If you have John Hancock
       installed on your system, and it is located in the directory:

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 29


            C:\BWAVE\JHANCOCK

       The only thing you need to place in this command line field is:

            C:\BWAVE\JHANCOCK\JH3.EXE

       The reader  does not  pass any command line parameters to the external
       tagline manager.

       There are  many external  tagline managers  available on  BBS systems.
       You can  download a  few from  our Blue Wave Support BBS, or find them
       locally.   At any  rate, the  documentation for these tagline managers
       must indicate  that they  are "John  Hancock-compatible", or that they
       specifically mention  Blue Wave  as one  of the mail readers they work
       with.

       For more  information about  taglines and  how you  can customize  the
       reader to  use taglines  and tagline files in extremely flexible ways,
       please see  the Table  of Contents  for the proper Chapter and Section
       dealing with "Creating Custom Tagline Files".



































                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 30

                   ----------------------------------------------------------
                   Chapter 7:  FILES CREATED, USED, & MAINTAINED BY BLUE WAVE
                   ----------------------------------------------------------


       The following chapter describes the names of the files that are
       created by the mail reader, what they are used for, and what you
       should do if they are accidentally deleted.

       Section 7.1  List of Files and their Purpose

       File Name      :    BWAVEDOS.CFG
       Version(s)     :    DOS
       Directory      :    \BWAVE
       Description    :    This is  the default  configuration file  used  by
                           Blue Wave/DOS.   If  no configuration file name is
                           given on the command line, this file will be used.
                           If you  accidentally delete  this file,  the  mail
                           reader will rebuild it for you.

       File Name      :    BWAVEOS2.CFG
       Version(s)     :    OS/2
       Directory      :    \BWAVE
       Description    :    This is  the default  configuration file  used  by
                           Blue Wave/OS2.   If  no configuration file name is
                           given on the command line, this file will be used.
                           If you  accidentally delete  this file,  the  mail
                           reader will rebuild it for you.

       File Name      :    BWAVE386.CFG
       Version(s)     :    386
       Directory      :    \BWAVE
       Description    :    This is  the default  configuration file  used  by
                           Blue Wave/386.   If  no configuration file name is
                           given on the command line, this file will be used.
                           If you  accidentally delete  this file,  the  mail
                           reader will rebuild it for you.

       File Name      :    BWAVE386.VMC
       Version(s)     :    386
       Directory      :    \BWAVE
       Description    :    This text  file contains configuration information
                           for  controlling   the  way  DOS/4GW  operates  in
                           conjunction  with   Blue  Wave/386.      This   is
                           considered an 'advanced' configuration item.  More
                           details about  this  file  can  be  found  in  the
                           "ADVANCED CONFIGURATION  ITEMS" chapter, or in the
                           file BWAVE386.VMC  file itself.   The  mail reader
                           will function  just fine without this file;  it is
                           completely optional.   It  serves not only to fine
                           tune the memory usage of the DOS/4GW DOS Extender,
                           but  also  to  enable  'virtual  memory  swapping"
                           features of this mail reader.  If you accidentally
                           delete this  file, it  can be  unpacked  from  the
                           distribution archive by selecting "Program Files".

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 31


       File Name      :    *.INI
       Version(s)     :    ALL
       Directory      :    \BWAVE\DATA
       Description    :    All *.INI  files that  are located in the reader's
                           DATA  directory  are  'Preferences'  configuration
                           files.   They hold  the preferences  settings  and
                           message filter  definitions  for  each  host  mail
                           system.   If these  are accidentally  deleted, you
                           will have  to rebuild them through the Preferences
                           Menu system  in the  reader's  Setup/Configuration
                           Menu.  The Default Preferences are stored in files
                           called _BW_???_.INI,  where '???' is one of either
                           DOS, 386, or OS2.

       File Name      :    _BWCOLOR.CFG
       Version(s)     :    ALL
       Directory      :    \BWAVE\DATA
       Description    :    This file  holds the  color configuration data for
                           the mail  reader.   If this  file is  accidentally
                           deleted,  the  mail  reader  will  revert  to  the
                           default color  scheme.   You will  need to use the
                           custom configuration  menus in the reader setup to
                           recreate your custom color configurations.

       File Name      :    PKTSTATS.BW
       Version(s)     :    ALL
       Directory      :    \BWAVE\DATA
       Description    :    This file holds information about each of the mail
                           packets that  you have  opened through  the Packet
                           Manager  selection   window.    If  this  file  is
                           deleted, the  mail reader will rebuild it for you.
                           However, all  data about  the mail packets in your
                           download directory  will be lost until you re-open
                           them.

       File Name      :    *.INF
       Version(s)     :    ALL
       Directory      :    \BWAVE\DATA
       Description    :    Each time  you open  a mail  packet  from  a  host
                           system, the information about the system is copied
                           to a  PACKETNAME.INI file  in  the  reader's  data
                           directory.   The main purpose of these files is to
                           allow you  to use  the "Reply Packet Manager" menu
                           without the need to open a mail packet from a host
                           mail system.  The mail reader allows you to delete
                           these files  from the  "Reply Packet Manager" host
                           selection window.   You  can delete these files if
                           you like;  they will be re-created when you open a
                           mail packet from that particular host system.

       File Name      :    _DEFAULT.ADR
       Version(s)     :    ALL
       Directory      :    \BWAVE\DATA


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 32

       Description    :    This file  contains the  reader's address book and
                           mailing lists.    If  this  file  is  accidentally
                           deleted, you  will lose  all of  the entries  that
                           were once in the address book.  You must re-create
                           your address  book using  the Address  Book Editor
                           within the  mail reader.   The address book editor
                           is accessed  by pressing  <Ctrl-G> at any time the
                           mail reader is loaded.



       Section 7.2  Creating Keyword Search Files

       One of  the most powerful aspects of The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader
       is its keyword searching capabilities.  Many genealogists use the mail
       reader's keyword file searching capabilities to research family trees,
       and  others   use  the   reader's  keyword  searching  facilities  for
       performing routines searches on their favorite hobbies or interests.

       While reading messages in the mail reader, you can search for keywords
       manually --  that is,  you enter  a keyword on-the-spot --, or through
       the use of a keyword search file.

       Keyword searches  by file  are initiated by pressing <K> while reading
       messages in  a message area, or by pressing <Alt-G>, <Alt-T>, or <Alt-
       A> at  the reader's  Area Selection  Menu, followed  by  choosing  the
       Keyword File search method.

       You can  use keyword  search files  to store keywords which you search
       for on  a regular basis.  Through the reader's Preferences system, you
       can define  a default keyword search file globally, by message packet,
       or by  each individual  area within a message packet.  Note that these
       are only  the default  keyword search file that will be used;  you can
       always manually  type the  name of  a keyword  search  file  into  the
       dialogue box  that appears  when you  choose to perform a keyword file
       search.

       Keyword search  files need  to be  created with  an ASCII file editor,
       such as  DOS's EDIT.COM,  OS/2's  System  Editor  (E.EXE),    or  TED3
       (supplied with the DOS and 386 mail reader).  A keyword search file is
       simply a  list of  keywords that  you would  like to  search for.  Any
       number of keywords can be entered into one file.  The mail reader will
       search for all of the keywords at one time.

       A sample  keyword search  file was supplied with your mail reader.  It
       should have  been installed  to the  main  reader  directory  (usually
       C:\BWAVE\DEFAULT.KEY).   There are  several examples  contained within
       this file.   Simply load DEFAULT.KEY into a text editor and edit it to
       your heart's content.

       If you  do not  have a  sample keyword  search file  by  the  name  of
       DEFAULT.KEY  located   in  your   main  reader   directory,  use   the
       installation program to unpack "Sample Keyword/Tagline/Welcome" files.



                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 33


       Section 7.3  Creating Tagline Files

       Blue Wave's  internal tagline  manager is one of the best available in
       an offline  mail reader.  A tagline is simply a one-line quip or quote
       which is  attached at  the end  of any messages that you enter through
       the mail  reader.   Taglines can  be turned off altogether through the
       Preferences menu in the reader Setup/Configuration section.

       All taglines  are stored  ASCII  text  files,  which  you  can  create
       yourself.   A sample  tagline file  should have  been installed by the
       installation utility  if "Sample  Keyword/Tagline/Welcome"  files  was
       selected during  installation.   A file called DEFAULT.TAG should have
       been placed into your main reader directory.

       A tagline  file simply  consists of  a list of taglines, one per line.
       Each line  in the  tagline selection  file that  does not begin with a
       comment line  (a line  beginning with  a semi-colon (;)) and that does
       not begin  with [COMMENT], [ALTLIST], or [EXTERNAL] will be considered
       a valid tagline.

       The reader  ignores all  characters past  column  70  in  the  tagline
       selection file.   You  should keep all lines shorter than this or they
       will be truncated when loaded by the reader.

       There are several tokens that can be used inside of a tagline file for
       complete customization.   A  complete tagline  menu system even can be
       built through the use of Blue Wave's internal tagline manager.

       The [COMMENT] Token
       -------------------
            The [COMMENT]  token can be used to place comments in the tagline
            selection window.   Any  line beginning  with [COMMENT]  will  be
            displayed as-is in the tagline selection window.  It will be non-
            selectable as a tagline, but the reader will search for text in a
            comment line  when using  the <Alt-S> search.  This can be useful
            if you  want to  divide your tagline file into groups or sections
            of related taglines.

       The [EXTERNAL] Token
       --------------------
            Any line beginning with [EXTERNAL], when highlighted and selected
            from the  tagline selection  window, will  cause  the  reader  to
            execute the External Tagline Manager command line, defined in the
            reader's Setup/Configuration  menu.   A sample tagline file entry
            might look like this:

                 [EXTERNAL]Press <Enter> here to load Tagline Manager

       The [ALTLIST] Token
       -------------------
            The [ALTLIST]  token gives  the  tagline  selection  process  its
            greatest power  and flexibility.    The  following  tagline  file
            entry:


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 34

                 [ALTLIST]C:\BWAVE\STARTREK.TAG

            when highlighted  and selected from the tagline selection window,
            will cause  the reader  to load  an alternate tagline file called
            STARTREK.TAG in  your C:\BWAVE  directory.   Using these  command
            tokens appropriately  will give  you the  power to build your own
            tagline selection "menu tree".


       While reading  messages, pressing  <Alt-A> or  <A> will  allow you  to
       'adopt' (read:  steal) taglines  directly out of messages that you are
       viewing on  the screen.  This will allow you to quickly build your own
       tagline collection.











































                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 35

                             ------------------------------------------------
                             Chapter 8:  COMMONLY ASKED QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
                             ------------------------------------------------


       This section  of the  documentation will  attempt to answer frequently
       asked questions  about The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader.  In addition
       to the information provided here, the Blue Wave Support BBS will begin
       carrying a  Frequently  Asked  Questions  file  to  be  available  for
       download.   We intend  on keeping this file up to date with the latest
       information and answers for problem reports.  Look for BLUEWAVE.FAQ on
       our support BBS in file area #1 after September 1, 1995.


       QUESTION: While I  like Blue  Wave very  much, I very much dislike the
                 TED3 editor  that is  supplied with  it.   TED3 doesn't even
                 have word-wrap.  Can I use another editor with Blue Wave?

       ANSWER:   Yes.   You can use a full word processor like WordPerfect or
                 WordStar as  long as  you save the messages/replies in ASCII
                 format so the invisible printer codes, margin settings, etc.
                 are not  embedded into  them like  in normal  WordPerfect or
                 WordStar files.

                 We recommend  something smaller, however, because for simple
                 ASCII message  writing, these  word processors  may be over-
                 kill.     Most  people   use  smaller   ASCII  text  editors
                 successfully with Blue Wave.

                 One of  the most popular is Qedit because of its small size;
                 yet it  is a  full-featured ASCII  text editor.  Other folks
                 prefer to  use Breeze,  Boxer, Sedit, or EZQuote.  There are
                 many nice  ShareWare or  FreeWare editors  to  choose  from.
                 Download some, test them, and choose the one you like best.

                 Please see  the  section  in  this  documentation  regarding
                 "Message Editor  Command Line",  and the online help for the
                 Message Editor  Command  Line  for  information  on  how  to
                 install  your   own  message  editor.    If  you  are  using
                 WordPerfect  v5.x,   please  see  the  "KNOWN  PROBLEMS  AND
                 INCOMPATIBILITIES" section of the documentation.


       QUESTION: Why doesn't Blue Wave support long Internet addresses?

       ANSWER:   The problem  is software  incompatibility.  The Internet was
                 originally developed by the US Government, and then given to
                 universities for educational purposes.  The Internet runs on
                 software that,  by design, is incompatible with the software
                 FidoNet and  most other  "hobbyist" networks use.  Blue Wave
                 was designed  for FidoNet,  to FidoNet  specifications years
                 before anyone  ever thought  the Internet  would someday  be
                 used on  personal computers.   That's  why  there  are  UUCP
                 gateways  in   FidoNet.    A  gateway  is  a  translator  or
                 interpreter.   It translates  Internet messages into FidoNet

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 36

                 messages, and  vice versa,  but the  incompatibility in  the
                 address length  still  exists  due  to  differences  between
                 software design.   Basically,  the TO:  field  in  the  mail
                 reader cannot  be increased  any more than 35 characters (25
                 characters for  QWK-formatted mail packets) because it would
                 do no  good.   The host  mail systems  would not  be able to
                 handle a  message that had more that their maximum character
                 capability.   This is  a problem  we have to live with until
                 the time  comes, if  ever,  when  FidoNet  can  develop  new
                 network software and specifications.


       QUESTION: Is there  anyway I  can get  around  the  limitation  of  25
                 character TO: fields in QWK-style mail packets?

       ANSWER:   Maybe.  Many (most?) QWK-style mail doors now support longer
                 TO: fields  through the  use of a simple work-around.  Enter
                 the FROM:,  and SUBJ:  fields as  normal.  In the TO: field,
                 enter as much of the name as will fit into the editing field
                 (25 characters).   Note  that some QWK mail doors will allow
                 you to  leave  this  field  blank,  so  you  might  want  to
                 experiment with this.

                 Next, when you reach the message editor, enter the following
                 text on  the FIRST  line of  the message,  and a  blank line
                 immediately following that:

                 To: someone@somewhere.very.far.away

                 The above  line is indented in this documentation due to the
                 text formatting.   The  "To: <address>" text should actually
                 appear at  the  far  left  margin,  in  column  number  one.
                 Remember to  leave at  least one  blank line  after this, as
                 most mail systems will not work properly without it.






















                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 37

                                     ----------------------------------------
                                     Chapter 9:  ADVANCED CONFIGURATION ITEMS
                                     ----------------------------------------


       The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader has several configuration items that
       are intended  for the  more advanced  user.   USE EXTREME CAUTION WHEN
       CHANGING THESE  ITEMS, as one wrong move could render your setup -- or
       your entire system -- unusable!


       Section 9.1  DOS Mail Reader

       Due to the constraints of the MS-DOS operating system (including other
       DOS-compatible operating  systems, such  as IBM's  PC-DOS and Novell's
       Novell DOS),  the memory  available to  the reader  at any one time is
       limited to  640K, minus any TSR (memory resident) programs loaded from
       your AUTOEXEC.BAT  file, hardware or software drivers loaded from your
       CONFIG.SYS file, and the memory that DOS itself uses.

       At certain  points during  the execution  of the reader, approximately
       400K of  memory can  be used.   The  amount of  memory required by the
       reader varies  with the  number of message areas contained in the mail
       packet and the number of messages contained in any one message area.

       Because of  the memory  demands of the DOS reader, it may be necessary
       to utilize  the reader's  built-in memory swapping system.  The memory
       swapping system  can free  all but 4K of the memory used by the reader
       when shelling  to DOS  or executing  an external program (such as text
       editors and archive compression and decompression programs).

       The memory  swapping system  is able to utilize expanded (EMS) memory,
       extended (XMS) memory, or a disk file to temporarily hold the contents
       of memory  while an  external program  is running.  If you have EMS or
       XMS memory  available, it  would be to your advantage to configure the
       reader to  use this  extra memory for quick swapping.  If neither type
       is available,  a disk  file can be used.  The temporary swap file will
       consume about  400K, and  will be  stored in  the directory  you  have
       configured as the reader's Swap Directory.

       To configure  the various memory swapping options, refer to the Memory
       Swapping Options  item under  the Global setup menu.  To configure the
       reader's swap  directory, refer to the Swap Directory option under the
       Directories setup menu.


       Section 9.2  386 Mail Reader

       The 386  reader loads  an advanced memory manager, DOS/4GW by Rational
       Systems (DOS4GW.EXE),  to allow it to run in protected mode and access
       up to  16MB of  extended memory.   You  do not  need to  load the  DOS
       HIMEM.SYS and  EMM386.EXE drivers  in order  for DOS/4GW  to  operate,
       though DOS/4GW will work just fine with those drivers loaded (and vice
       versa).


                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 38

       Normally, the  386 reader will not require more than 2MB of memory, as
       2MB should  be more  than enough  to handle any mail packet that comes
       your way.   However,  if you  do need  more memory,  but  your  system
       doesn't have it, DOS/4GW can use what is called a "virtual memory swap
       file".  Simply put, it can create a disk file that is treated as extra
       memory.

       The virtual  memory swap  file can be created by placing a file called
       BWAVE386.VMC into the same directory that contains BWAVE386.EXE.  This
       is a  configuration file for DOS/4GW containing instructions on how to
       create the  swap file.   A sample BWAVE386.VMC file is included in the
       reader's distribution  archive (it should have been placed in the main
       reader directory during the installation procedure), and contains full
       descriptions of  each available  option.  Use a text editor to examine
       this file, and to make any necessary changes.


       Section 9.3  OS/2 Mail Reader

       When executing  external programs (editors, archivers, spell checkers,
       etc.), the  OS/2 reader  will normally  spawn a  copy of  the  command
       processor, CMD.EXE  (or 4OS2.EXE if you are using JP Software's 4OS2).
       This allows  the OS/2  reader to use DOS and Windows programs, as well
       as OS/2  programs.   The disadvantage  to this procedure is that it is
       slow, since  the command processor has to be loaded in addition to the
       program being executed.

       If you  are using  native OS/2 programs (such as ZIP.EXE and UNZIP.EXE
       from the  Info-ZIP Project),  you can  tell the  reader to  bypass the
       command processor and execute the programs directly.  The advantage is
       that native OS/2 programs will load instantly.

       To accomplish  this, place  an exclamation point ("!") in front of the
       defined command line.  For example:

            !C:\UTIL\ZIP.EXE -jk9 "@F" "@I"

       would cause the OS/2 reader to execute ZIP.EXE directly, bypassing the
       command processor.

















                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 39

                            -------------------------------------------------
                            Chapter 10:  KNOWN PROBLEMS AND INCOMPATIBILITIES
                            -------------------------------------------------


       Section 10.1  DOS Reader

       PROBLEM:  If you  are using  the SmartDrive  disk cache (SMARTDRV.EXE)
                 and have  Exploding Windows enabled, you may find the reader
                 occasionally locking  up when attempting to open a window on
                 the screen.

       SOLUTION: Disable Exploding Windows.

       PROBLEM:  If you  are using  WordPerfect v5.x  as your text editor and
                 have memory swapping enabled, WordPerfect will complain that
                 there are not enough file handles.

       SOLUTION: Place an  "@" character  in front  of the  command line that
                 executes WordPerfect.   This  causes the  reader to  use the
                 command processor, COMMAND.COM (or 4DOS.COM if you are using
                 JP Software's 4DOS), to execute WordPerfect.


       Section 10.2  386 Reader

       PROBLEM:  DOS/4GW will  not operate correctly on your system, refusing
                 to load and execute the reader.

       SOLUTION: Try eliminating  some TSR  (memory  resident)  programs  and
                 device drivers  from your AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS files,
                 as one  or  more  of  these  may  be  interfering  with  the
                 operation of  DOS/4GW.   (If you  are using  MS-DOS  6.0  or
                 later, or  PC-DOS 6.1  or later,  you have a more convenient
                 method:   Pressing the  <F5> key  after the  "Starting  DOS"
                 message is  displayed will  completely bypass the loading of
                 AUTOEXEC.BAT and  CONFIG.SYS, resulting  in a  "bare" system
                 configuration.)

                 If eliminating  TSRs and  device drivers  doesn't solve  the
                 problem, you  may be  faced with  the  problem  of  hardware
                 incompatibility.   Some systems  simply refuse  to cooperate
                 with DOS/4GW  and other DOS extenders.  In such cases, there
                 is very  little that can be done, other than to replace your
                 hardware (or switch to a different version of the reader).


       Section 10.3  OS/2 Reader

       PROBLEM:  Using Artisoft's  LANtastic for OS/2 peer-to-peer networking
                 software, the  workstation hangs  with  a  TRAP  error  when
                 attempting to load a large file over the network.

       SOLUTION: This is apparently a problem with LANtastic for OS/2.  Until
                 this problem  can be  corrected by Artisoft, a workaround is

                 --------------------------------------------------
                 The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader, v2.30;  Page 40

                 to move  the file to the local workstation before attempting
                 to load it into the reader.

       PROBLEM:  If you  have configured  the reader  to  use  high-intensity
                 background colors,  the display will show blinking text on a
                 low-intensity background  after switching to another process
                 (via <Alt-Esc> or <Ctrl-Esc> and back again.

       SOLUTION: This problem  usually shows  up with  video cards that use a
                 SuperVGA chipset  from S3.   Sometimes,  switching away  and
                 back again  will put the display back to normal; most times,
                 it won't.   Until  the S3  video drivers are fixed, the only
                 available solution  is to  not use high-intensity background
                 colors.










































